Predicting Volatile Acidity in wine using other chemical measurements¶

Introduction¶

The objective of this project is to predict the level of Volatile Acidity in a wine using other independent chemical properties of the wine using the Wine Quality datasets from the UCI Machine Learning Repository: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/machine-learning-databases/wine-quality/ (Cortez et al., 2009).

  • Overview section describes the dataset used and the features in this dataset.
  • Data Preparation section covers data cleaning and data preparation steps.
  • Data Exploration section explores dataset features and their inter-relationships.
  • Statistical Modeling and Performance Evaluation section first fits a full multiple linear regression model and performs diagnostic checks. Next, we perform backwards variable selection using p-values to obtain a reduced model, after which we perform another set of diagnostic checks on the reduced model.
  • Summary and Conclusions section provides a summary of the work and presents any findings.

Overview¶

Data Source¶

The UCI Machine Learning Repository provides two datasets of objective tests on red and white wine samples from Northern Portugal that all fall under the Vinho Verde DOC (denominao de origem controlada) appellation. There are 1599 observations on red wines and 4898 observations on white wines. For the purpose of this project we will combine these into one dataset, with red and white wine type values added respectively.

Project Aim¶

The aim of this project is to apply multiple linear regression to try and predict the level of Volatile Acidity in a wine based off of other independent variables of the same wine.

Target Feature¶

The datasets contain 10 independent measurements, and one categorical variable (wine rating), and one target variable. The target variable in this case is the Volatile Acidity level of the wine. Volatile Acidity "is a measure of the low molecular weight, or steam-distillable, fatty acids in wine, with by far the major acid being acetic acid (>93%)".

Volatile Acidity (VA) is a byproduct of long fermentation times and oxygen exposure during winemaking. Typically considered a fault above certain levels, VA in small amounts can add red fruit aromas to wines, and starts to smell like vinegar and nail-polish remover in higher concentrations. Recently, minimal-intervention wine techniques have started to become very trendy in the wine world, with wine made in the style often referred to as "natural wine", and some wine makers have switched to more rustic production methods including abandoning exogenous sulfur additions and using wild yeasts instead of controlled yeast additions for fermentation. Criticisms of "natural wine" typically mention high levels of VA as the main fault with these wines. As such, it will be interesting to explore whether sulfur dioxide levels are inversely correlated with VA.

Desriptive Features¶

The variables are as follows (from winequality.names file) 1 - fixed acidity (continuous, measure of non-volatile acids in wine, inc. tartaric acid, malic acid, lactic acid) 2 - volatile acidity (continuous, measure of volatile acids in wine, mostly acetic acid) 3 - citric acid (continuous) 4 - residual sugar (continuous, measure of unfermented sugars from grapes) 5 - chlorides (continuous) 6 - free sulfur dioxide (continuous, measure of SO2 in its free form in wine) 7 - total sulfur dioxide (continuous, total overall sulfur) 8 - density (continuous, density of wine) 9 - pH (continuous) 10 - sulphates (continuous) 11 - alcohol (continuous, as a percentage of the wine) 12 - quality (discrete, subjective rating of wine by wine critics)

Data Preparation¶

The data in this case is not very difficult to prepare. We will combine the csv files for both red and white wine together, giving them their own value for red and white wine as another column in the combined data frame.

# Read in data

attribNames = [
    'fixed_acidity',
    'volatile_acidity',
    'citric_acid',
    'residual_sugar',
    'chlorides',
    'free_sulfur_dioxide',
    'total_sulfur_dioxide',
    'density',
    'ph',
    'sulphates',
    'alcohol',
    'quality',
]
url = (
    "https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/machine-learning-databases/wine-quality/winequality-white.csv",
    "https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/machine-learning-databases/wine-quality/winequality-red.csv",
)
red_data = pd.read_csv(url[0], sep = ';', skiprows=1, names = attribNames, header = None)
white_data = pd.read_csv(url[1], sep = ';', skiprows=1, names = attribNames, header = None)

# Add 'Red' and 'White' attribute to respective data sets
column_length = len(red_data['ph'])
red_data['wine_type'] = pd.Series(np.random.randn(column_length), index=red_data.index)
red_data.loc[:,'wine_type'] = 'red'

column_length = len(white_data['ph'])
white_data['wine_type'] = pd.Series(np.random.randn(column_length), index=white_data.index)
white_data.loc[:,'wine_type'] = 'white'


# Join data sets together
data = pd.concat([red_data, white_data])

# Display random 10 rows
data.sample(10, random_state=999)

Statistical Modeling and Performance Evaluation¶

Full Model¶

We fit a multiple linear regression that predicts 'volatile-acidity' using all of the available features except 'quality'. Quality rating is subjective, likely predicts our target variable, and we don't want it skewing our results.

def plot_line(axis, slope, intercept, **kargs):
    xmin, xmax = axis.get_xlim()
    plt.plot([xmin, xmax], [xmin*slope+intercept, xmax*slope+intercept], **kargs)

Backwards feature selection¶

Note that this backwards feature selection code was written by Dr Vural Aksakalli of RMIT University

In [25]:
## create the patsy model description from formula
patsy_description = patsy.ModelDesc.from_formula(formula_string_encoded)

# initialize feature-selected fit to full model
linreg_fit = model_full_fitted

# do backwards elimination using p-values
p_val_cutoff = 0.05

## WARNING 1: The code below assumes that the Intercept term is present in the model.
## WARNING 2: It will work only with main effects and two-way interactions, if any.

print('\nPerforming backwards feature selection using p-values:')

while True:

    # uncomment the line below if you would like to see the regression summary
    # in each step:
    ### print(linreg_fit.summary())

    pval_series = linreg_fit.pvalues.drop(labels='Intercept')
    pval_series = pval_series.sort_values(ascending=False)
    term = pval_series.index[0]
    pval = pval_series[0]
    if (pval < p_val_cutoff):
        break
    term_components = term.split(':')
    print(f'\nRemoving term "{term}" with p-value {pval:.4}')
    if (len(term_components) == 1): ## this is a main effect term
        patsy_description.rhs_termlist.remove(patsy.Term([patsy.EvalFactor(term_components[0])]))    
    else: ## this is an interaction term
        patsy_description.rhs_termlist.remove(patsy.Term([patsy.EvalFactor(term_components[0]), 
                                                        patsy.EvalFactor(term_components[1])]))    
        
    linreg_fit = smf.ols(formula=patsy_description, data=data_encoded).fit()
    
###
## this is the clean fit after backwards elimination
model_reduced_fitted = smf.ols(formula = patsy_description, data = data_encoded).fit()
###
    
#########
print("\n***")
print(model_reduced_fitted.summary())
print("***")
print(f"Regression number of terms: {len(model_reduced_fitted.model.exog_names)}")
print(f"Regression F-distribution p-value: {model_reduced_fitted.f_pvalue:.4f}")
print(f"Regression R-squared: {model_reduced_fitted.rsquared:.4f}")
print(f"Regression Adjusted R-squared: {model_reduced_fitted.rsquared_adj:.4f}")

Summary and Conclusions¶

When we look at the predicted VA vs actual VA graph, we can see a fairly good prediction of VA until we reach the upper bounds of VA, (3rd quartile and above according to the box plot of Volatile Acidity). When we consider that our adjusted R2 value is .582 (.583 with backward feature selection) and that our residuals aren't skewed and don't suggest a poor fit, it seems we have a reasonable model for predicting Volatile Acidity. Although it seemed that we were able to find some good relationships between Volatile Acidity and other variables in the data exploration section, the majority of the data fell in the middle of the two extremes for these relationships, and a wasn't strong enough predictor to give us a tightly fitting prediction. The reality is that wine is the result of biological processes that we don't fully understand, and as such we can't expect to see perfect predictions of its chemical compounds. If we were able to achieve such a thing, then the fine wine industry would be worth far less money than it is today, as the prestigious wines of Burgundy and Barolo could be produced in any laboratory and backyard. One also must consider that the data only represented a very small part of the world of wine, so it remains to be seen what kind of models could be calculated with a larger dataset.
